### Git

clone repo - git clone https://github.com/project/app.git

Working Directory → Staging Area → Repository (below)

Add files - git add . (“Okay, I see this file. Ready to save it.”)

commit - git commit -m "added feature" (Commit = Save point in history)

Git stores:

what changed
when
who made change

push - git push origin main (Uploads your code to GitHub.)


Breakdown:
Part	  Meaning
push	  send code
origin	your GitHub repo
main	  branch name

branching - git checkout -b feature-login


##Configure Git (Important Step)

Set your identity (used in commits):

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your@email.com"

git config --list

Generate SSH key

ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"

This creates:

~/.ssh/id_ed25519
~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
id_ed25519 = private key, never share
id_ed25519.pub = public key, safe to add to GitHub


Start the SSH agent

eval "$(ssh-agent -s)" - This starts a background process that manages your key.

Then add your private key:

ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519

If you set a passphrase, it will ask for it here.

verify key loaded - ssh-add -l


cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub - show the public key

Add the public key to GitHub

In GitHub:

click your profile picture
go to Settings
open SSH and GPG keys
click New SSH key
title: something like Ubuntu DevSecOps Lab
paste the key
save

Now GitHub knows your machine.

ssh -T git@github.com - test connection



